# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cors-misconfiguration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In computing, **cross-origin resource sharing** (**CORS**) is a mechanism to safely bypass the same-origin policy; that is, it allows a web page to access restricted resources from a web server on a domain name different from the domain that served the web page.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A web page may freely embed cross-origin images, stylesheets, scripts, iframes, and videos.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Certain "cross-domain" HTTP requests, notably Ajax requests, are forbidden by default by the same-origin security policy.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS defines a way in which a web browser and server can interact to determine whether it is safe to allow the cross-origin request.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] It allows for more freedom and functionality than purely same-origin requests, but is more secure than simply allowing all cross-origin requests.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The specification for CORS is included as part of the WHATWG's Fetch Living Standard.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] This specification describes how CORS is currently implemented in browsers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] An earlier specification was published as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Servers can also notify clients whether "credentials" (including Cookies and HTTP Authentication data) should be sent with requests.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Suppose a user visits http://www.example.com and the page attempts a cross-origin request to fetch data from http://service.example.com.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A CORS-compatible browser will attempt to make a cross-origin request to service.example.com as follows.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A wildcard same-origin policy is appropriate when a page or API response is intended to be accessible to any code on any site.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A freely available web font on a public hosting service like Google Fonts is an example.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The value of "*" is special in that it does not allow requests to supply credentials, meaning that it does not allow HTTP authentication, client-side SSL certificates, or cookies to be sent in the cross-domain request.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Note that in the CORS architecture, the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header is being set by the external web service (*service.example.com*), not the original web application server (*www.example.com*).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Here, *service.example.com* uses CORS to permit the browser to authorize *www.example.com* to make requests to *service.example.com*.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If a site specifies the header "Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:true", third-party sites may be able to carry out privileged actions and retrieve sensitive information.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] When performing certain types of cross-domain Ajax requests, modern browsers that support CORS will initiate an extra "preflight" request to determine whether they have permission to perform the action.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin requests are preflighted this way because they may have implications to user data.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The browser will then make the actual request.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If service.example.com does not accept cross-site requests from this origin then it will respond with error to the OPTIONS request and the browser will not make the actual request.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin support was originally proposed by Matt Oshry, Brad Porter, and Michael Bodell of Tellme Networks in March 2004 for inclusion in VoiceXML 2.1 to allow safe cross-origin data requests by VoiceXML browsers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The mechanism was deemed general in nature and not specific to VoiceXML and was subsequently separated into an implementation NOTE.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The WebApps Working Group of the W3C with participation from the major browser vendors began to formalize the NOTE into a W3C Working Draft on track toward formal W3C Recommendation status.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In May 2006 the first W3C Working Draft was submitted.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In March 2009 the draft was renamed to "Cross-Origin Resource Sharing" and in January 2014 it was accepted as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The main advantage of JSONP was its ability to work on legacy browsers which predate CORS support (Opera Mini and Internet Explorer 9 and earlier).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS is now supported by most modern web browsers, and can be used as a modern alternative to the JSONP pattern.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] The following cheat sheet serves as a guide for implementing HTML 5 in a secure fashion.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] Web Messaging (also known as Cross Domain Messaging) provides a means of messaging between documents from different origins in a way that is generally safer than the multiple hacks used in the past to accomplish this task.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] Attack is described in detail in this article.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] To summarize, it's the capacity to act on parent page's content or location from a newly opened page via the back link exposed by the **opener** JavaScript object instance.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] It applies to an HTML link or a JavaScript `window.open` function using the attribute/instruction `target` to specify a target loading location that does not replace the current location and then makes the current window/tab available.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] All links are prevented from targeting other browsing contexts.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] All features that trigger automatically are blocked.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] It is possible to have a fine-grained control over `iframe` capabilities using the value of the `sandbox` attribute.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] Text areas and input fields for PII (name, email, address, phone number) and login credentials (username, password) should be prevented from being stored in the browser.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/html5-security-cheat-sheet] Consult the project OWASP Secure Headers in order to obtains the list of HTTP security headers that an application should use to enable defenses at browser level.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] In computing, the **same-origin policy** (**SOP**) is a concept in the web application security model.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Under the policy, a web browser permits scripts contained in a first web page to access data in a second web page, but only if both web pages have the same *origin*.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] An origin is defined as a combination of URI scheme, host name, and port number.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This policy prevents a malicious script on one page from obtaining access to sensitive data on another web page through that page's Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This mechanism bears a particular significance for modern web applications that extensively depend on HTTPS cookies to maintain authenticated user sessions, as servers act based on the HTTP cookie information to reveal sensitive information or perform state-changing actions.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] A strict separation between content provided by unrelated sites must be maintained on the client-side to prevent the loss of data confidentiality or integrity.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy applies only to scripts.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This means that resources such as images, CSS, and dynamically loaded scripts can be accessed across origins via the corresponding HTML tags (with fonts being a notable exception).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Attacks take advantage of the fact that the same origin policy does not apply to HTML tags.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] There are some mechanisms available to relax the SOP; one of them is cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The concept of same-origin policy was introduced by Netscape Navigator 2.02 in 1995, shortly after the introduction of JavaScript in Netscape 2.0.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] JavaScript enabled scripting on web pages, and in particular programmatic access to the DOM.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The policy was originally designed to protect access to the DOM, but has since been broadened to protect sensitive parts of the global JavaScript object.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] All modern browsers implement some form of the same-origin policy as it is an important security cornerstone.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The algorithm used to calculate the "origin" of a URI is specified in RFC 6454, Section 4.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] For absolute URIs, the origin is the triple {scheme, host, port}.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] If the URI does not use a hierarchical element as a naming authority (see RFC 3986, Section 3.2) or if the URI is not an absolute URI, then a globally unique identifier is used.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Two resources are considered to be of the same origin if and only if all these values are exactly the same.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] To illustrate, the following table gives an overview of typical outcomes for checks against the URL "**http://www.example.com/dir/page.html**".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Unlike other browsers, Internet Explorer does not include the port in the calculation of the origin, using the Security Zone in its place.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy protects against reusing authenticated sessions across origins.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The following example illustrates a potential security risk that could arise without the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Assume that a user is visiting a banking website and doesn't log out.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Then, the user goes to another site that has malicious JavaScript code that requests data from the banking site.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Because the user is still logged in on the banking site, the malicious code could do anything the user could do on the banking site.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] For example, it could get a list of the user's last transactions, create a new transaction, etc.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This is because, in the original spirit of a World Wide Web, browsers are required to tag along authentication details such as session cookies and platform-level kinds of the Authorization request header to the banking site based on the domain of the banking site.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The bank site owners would expect that regular browsers of users visiting the malicious site do not allow the code loaded from the malicious site access the banking session cookie or platform-level authorization.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] While it is true that JavaScript has no direct access to the banking session cookie, it could still send and receive requests to the banking site with the banking site's session cookie.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Same Origin Policy was introduced as a requirement for security-minded browsers to deny read access to responses from across origins, with the assumption that the majority of users choose to use compliant browsers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Counteracting the abuse of the write permission requires additional CSRF protections by the target sites.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] In some circumstances, the same-origin policy is too restrictive, posing problems for large websites that use multiple subdomains.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] At first, a number of workarounds such as using the fragment identifier or the `window.name` property were used to pass data between documents residing in different domains.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Netscape Navigator briefly contained a taint checking feature.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The feature was experimentally introduced in 1997 as part of Netscape 3.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The feature was turned off by default, but if enabled by a user it would allow websites to attempt to read JavaScript properties of windows and frames belonging to a different domain.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The browser would then ask the user whether to permit the access in question.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] If two windows (or frames) contain scripts that set domain to the same value, the same-origin policy is relaxed for these two windows, and each window can interact with the other.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] For example, cooperating scripts in documents loaded from orders.example.com and catalog.example.com might set their `document.domain` properties to “example.com”, thereby making the documents appear to have the same origin and enabling each document to read properties of the other.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Setting this property implicitly sets the port to null, which most browsers will interpret differently from port 80 or even an unspecified port.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] To assure that access will be allowed by the browser, set the document.domain property of both pages.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The `document.domain` concept was introduced as part of Netscape Navigator 3, released in 1996.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The other technique for relaxing the same-origin policy is standardized under the name cross-origin resource sharing (CORS).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This standard extends HTTP with a new `Origin` request header and a new `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] It allows servers to use a header to explicitly list origins that may request a file or to use a wildcard and allow a file to be requested by any site.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Browsers such as Firefox 3.5, Safari 4 and Internet Explorer 10 use this header to allow the cross-origin HTTP requests with XMLHttpRequest that would otherwise have been forbidden by the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Another technique, cross-document messaging, allows a script from one page to pass textual messages to a script on another page regardless of the script origins.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Calling the postMessage() method on a Window object asynchronously fires an "onmessage" event in that window, triggering any user-defined event handlers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] A script in one page still cannot directly access methods or variables in the other page, but they can communicate safely through this message-passing technique.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Since HTML `<script>` elements are allowed to retrieve and execute content from other domains, a page can bypass the same-origin policy and receive JSON data from a different domain by loading a resource that returns a JSONP payload.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] JSONP payloads consist of an internal JSON payload wrapped by a pre-defined function call.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] When the script resource is loaded by the browser, the designated callback function will be invoked to process the wrapped JSON payload.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Modern browsers will permit a script to connect to a WebSocket address without applying the same-origin policy.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] However, they recognize when a WebSocket URI is used, and insert an **Origin:** header into the request that indicates the origin of the script requesting the connection.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] To ensure cross-site security, the WebSocket server must verify that that origin is permitted to receive a reply.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The behavior of same-origin checks and related mechanisms is not well-defined in a number of corner cases such as for pseudo-protocols that do not have a clearly defined host name or port associated with their URLs (file:, data:, etc.).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This historically caused a fair number of security problems, such as the generally undesirable ability of any locally stored HTML file to access all other files on the disk, or communicate with any site on the Internet.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Lastly, certain types of attacks, such as DNS rebinding or server-side proxies, permit the host name check to be partly subverted, and make it possible for rogue web pages to directly interact with sites through addresses other than their "true", canonical origin.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The impact of such attacks is limited to very specific scenarios, since the browser still believes that it is interacting with the attacker's site, and therefore does not disclose third-party cookies or other sensitive information to the attacker.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Even when same-origin policy is in effect (without being relaxed by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing), certain cross-origin attacks can be performed.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] WebRTC can be used to find out the internal IP address of a victim.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] If attempting to connect to a cross-origin port, responses cannot be read in face of same-origin policy, but a JavaScript can still make inferences on whether the port is open or closed by checking if the onload/onerror event fires, or if we get a timeout.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This gives opportunities for cross-origin portscanning.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Further, JavaScript snippets can use techniques like cross-site leaks to exploit long-standing information leakages in the browser to infer information cross-origin.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] These attacks can be counteracted by implementing a Cross-Origin Resource Policy (CORP) header, which allows a website owner to block cross-origin or cross-site resources, like images, videos, and stylesheets.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] CORP can also block JavaScript-initiated `fetch` requests, but only if they are sent with the `no-cors` request mode.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] The same-origin policy does not prevent the browser from making GET, POST, OPTIONS, and TRACE requests; it only prevents the responses from being read by user code.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Therefore, if an endpoint uses one of these "safe" request methods to write information or perform an action on a user's behalf, it can be exploited by attackers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Note that the same-origin policy does not apply to cookies for historical reasons.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] If multiple adversarial sites are deployed on the same hostname with different port numbers, contrary to the SOP, all cookies set by any of the sites are shared.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] This can be used to leak users' session tokens and steal account information.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/same-origin-policy] Therefore, web services should be separated by differentiating subdomains rather than port numbers.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] A **browser engine** (also known as a **layout engine** or **rendering engine**) is a core software component of every major web browser.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] The primary job of a browser engine is to transform HTML documents and other resources of a web page into an interactive visual representation on a user's device.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] Besides "browser engine", two other related terms are commonly used: "layout engine" and "rendering engine".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] In theory, layout and rendering (or "painting") could be handled by different engines.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] In practice, however, these components are tightly coupled and rarely encountered on their own outside of the browser engine.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] In addition to layout and rendering, a browser engine enforces the security policy between documents, handles navigation through hyperlinks and data submitted through forms, and implements the document object model (DOM) exposed to scripts associated with the document.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] To provide a wide range of dynamic behavior for web pages, every major browser supports JavaScript.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] However, JavaScript is implemented as a separate JavaScript engine, which has enabled its usage elsewhere.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] In a browser, the two engines are coordinated via the DOM and Web IDL bindings.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] Browser engines are also used in non-browser applications.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] An email client needs one to display HTML email.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] Beginning in the 2010s, many apps have been created with the frameworks based on Google's Chromium project; each of these standalone apps functions much like a web app.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] The layout of a web page is typically specified by Cascading Style Sheets (CSS).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] Each style sheet is a series of rules for how the page should be presented.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] For example, some rules specify typography details, such as font, color, and text size, while others determine the placement of images.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] The engine combines all relevant CSS rules to calculate precise graphical coordinates and pixel values for the visual representation it will paint on the screen.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] The engine updates the visual representation in response to new events, including the user scrolling the page, content being asynchronously fetched, video playback, and canvas animations.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] It also may begin rendering before a page's resources are downloaded, which can result in visual changes as more data is received, such as images being gradually filled in or a flash of unstyled content.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] The following chart shows the duration of active development (when relevant new web standards continue to be added) for each engine in this section.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-browser-engine] Note that Gecko, WebKit, and Blink are still actively developed.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] A **web resource** is any identifiable resource (digital, physical, or abstract) present on or connected to the World Wide Web.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Resources are identified using Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] In the Semantic Web, web resources and their semantic properties are described using the Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] In the early specifications of the web (1990–1994), the term *resource* is barely used at all.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The web is designed as a network of more or less static addressable objects, basically files and documents, linked using Uniform Resource Locators (URLs).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] A web resource is implicitly defined as something which can be identified.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The identification serves two distinct purposes: naming and addressing; the latter only depends on a protocol.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] It is notable that RFC 1630 does not attempt to define at all the notion of resource; actually it barely uses the term besides its occurrence in Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), Uniform Resource Locator (URL), and Uniform Resource Name (URN), and still speaks about "Objects of the Network".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] RFC 1738 (December 1994) further specifies URLs, the term "Universal" being changed to "Uniform".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The document is making a more systematic use of *resource* to refer to objects which are "available", or "can be located and accessed" through the internet.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] There again, the term *resource* itself is not explicitly defined.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Although examples in this document were still limited to physical entities, the definition opened the door to more abstract resources.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Providing a concept is given an identity, and this identity is expressed by a well-formed URI (Uniform Resource Identifier, a superset of URLs), then a concept can be a resource as well.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] First released in 1999, RDF was first intended to describe resources, in other words to declare metadata of resources in a standard way.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] A RDF description of a resource is a set of triples (subject, predicate, object), where *subject* represents the resource to be described, *predicate* a type of property relevant to this resource, and *object* can be data or another resource.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The predicate itself is considered as a resource and identified by a URI.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Hence, properties like "title", "author" are represented in RDF as resources, which can be used, in a recursive way, as the subject of other triples.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Building on this recursive principle, RDF vocabularies, such as RDF Schema (RDFS), Web Ontology Language (OWL), and Simple Knowledge Organization System will pile up definitions of abstract resources such as classes, properties, concepts, all identified by URIs.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] RDF also specifies the definition of anonymous resources or blank nodes, which are not absolutely identified by URIs.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] URLs, particularly HTTP URIs, are frequently used to identify abstract resources, such as classes, properties or other kind of concepts.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Examples can be found in RDFS or OWL ontologies.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The URI specifications such as RFC 3986 left to the protocol specification the task of defining actions performed on the resources and they do not provide any answer to this question.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] But it has been answered that such a distinction is impossible to enforce in practice, and famous standard vocabularies provide counter-examples widely used.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] For example, the Dublin Core concepts such as "title", "publisher", "creator" are identified by "slash" URIs like `http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title`.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] The general question of which kind of resources HTTP URI should or should not identify has been formerly known in W3C as the httpRange-14 issue, following its name on the list defined by the (TAG).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] This allows vocabularies (like Dublin Core, FOAF, and Wordnet) to continue to use slash instead of hash for pragmatic reasons.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] While this compromise seems to have met a consensus in the Semantic Web community, some of its prominent members such as Pat Hayes have expressed concerns both on its technical feasibility and conceptual foundation.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] According to Patrick Hayes' viewpoint, the very distinction between "information resource" and "other resource" is impossible to find and should better not be specified at all, and ambiguity of the referent resource is inherent to URIs like to any naming mechanism.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] In RDF, "anybody can declare anything about anything".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] Resources are defined by formal descriptions which anyone can publish, copy, modify and publish over the web.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] It's an open issue to know if a resource should have an authoritative definition with clear and trustable ownership, and in this case, how to make this description technically distinct from other descriptions.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/web-resource] A parallel issue is how intellectual property may apply to such descriptions.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The concept behind `XMLHttpRequest` was conceived in 2000 by the developers of Microsoft Outlook.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The concept was then implemented within the Internet Explorer 5 browser (1999).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] However, the original syntax did not use the `XMLHttpRequest` identifier.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Instead, the developers used the identifiers `ActiveXObject("Msxml2.XMLHTTP")` and `ActiveXObject("Microsoft.XMLHTTP")`.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] As of Internet Explorer 7 (2006), all browsers support the `XMLHttpRequest` identifier.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The `XMLHttpRequest` identifier is now the *de facto* standard in all the major browsers, including Mozilla's Gecko layout engine (2002), Safari 1.2 (2004) and Opera 8.0 (2005).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) published a *Working Draft* specification for the `XMLHttpRequest` object on April 5, 2006.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] On February 25, 2008, the W3C published the *Working Draft Level 2* specification.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Level 2 added methods to monitor event progress, allow cross-site requests, and handle byte streams.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] At the end of 2011, the Level 2 specification was absorbed into the original specification.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] At the end of 2012, the WHATWG took over development and maintains a living document using Web IDL.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Aside from these general steps, `XMLHttpRequest` has many options to control how the request is sent and how the response is processed.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Custom header fields can be added to the request to indicate how the server should fulfill it, and data can be uploaded to the server by providing it in the "send" call.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The response can be parsed from the JSON format into a readily usable JavaScript object, or processed gradually as it arrives rather than waiting for the entire text.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The request can be aborted prematurely or set to fail if not completed in a specified amount of time.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] In the early development of the World Wide Web, it was found possible to breach users' security by the use of JavaScript to exchange information from one web site with that from another less reputable one.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] All modern browsers therefore implement a same origin policy that prevents many such attacks, such as cross-site scripting.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] `XMLHttpRequest` data is subject to this security policy, but sometimes web developers want to intentionally circumvent its restrictions.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] This is sometimes due to the legitimate use of subdomains as, for example, making an `XMLHttpRequest` from a page created by `foo.example.com` for information from `bar.example.com` will normally fail.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Various alternatives exist to circumvent this security feature, including using JSONP, Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) or alternatives with plugins such as Flash or Silverlight (both now deprecated).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Cross-origin XMLHttpRequest is specified in W3C's `XMLHttpRequest` Level 2 specification.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Internet Explorer did not implement CORS until version 10.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The two previous versions (8 and 9) offered similar functionality through the XDomainRequest (XDR) API.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] CORS is now supported by all modern browsers (desktop and mobile).
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The CORS protocol has several restrictions, with two models of support.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The *simple* model does not allow setting custom request headers and omits cookies.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Further, only the HEAD, GET and POST request methods are supported, and POST only allows the following MIME types: "text/plain", "application/x-www-urlencoded" and "multipart/form-data".
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Only "text/plain" was initially supported.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] The other model detects when one of the *non-simple* features are requested and sends a *pre-flight request* to the server to negotiate the feature.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Program flow using asynchronous XHR callbacks can present difficulty with readability and maintenance.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] ECMAScript 2015 (ES6) added the promise construct to simplify asynchronous logic.
[src:cors-misconfiguration/xmlhttprequest] Browsers have since implemented the alternative `fetch()` interface to achieve the same functionality as XHR using promises instead of callbacks.
